{"title_page": "Fascist (insult)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{more citations needed|date=October 2009}}\n{{Fascism sidebar|expanded=Related}}\n'''Fascist''' has been used as a [[pejorative]] [[epithet]] against a wide range of individuals, political movements, governments, public and private institutions since the emergence of [[fascism]] in [[Europe]] in the 1920s.\n\nThe widespread use of this term as an insult was noted as early as 1944, when British writer [[George Orwell]] commented that, in the [[United Kingdom]], \"the word 'Fascism' is almost entirely meaningless\" and that \"almost any English person would accept \u2018bully\u2019 as a synonym for \u2018Fascist\u2019.\"<ref>[[George Orwell]], [http://orwell.ru/library/articles/As_I_Please/english/efasc What is Fascism?], 1944</ref>\n\nIn the [[Soviet Union]], the epithets \"fascist\" and \"fascism\" were used to describe [[Anti-Sovietism|anti-Soviet]] activism and beliefs, such as [[enemy of the people|enemies of the people]]. This usage also spread to other [[Eastern bloc]] countries under Soviet [[Warsaw pact]] domination, such as [[East Germany]], where the [[Berlin Wall]] was known as the \"Anti-Fascist Protection Wall\". The term \"anti-fascist\" became ubiquitous in the Eastern bloc, where it became synonymous with the [[communist party]] line and denoted the struggle against [[dissenter]]s and against the broader [[Western world]].<ref name=\"Agethen\">{{cite book |last1= Agethen |first1= Manfred |last2= Jesse |first2= Eckhard |author-link2= Eckhard Jesse |last3= Neubert |first3= Ehrhart |year= 2002 |title= Der missbrauchte Antifaschismus |url= |location= Freiburg |publisher= Verlag Herder |page= |isbn= 978-3451280177 |author-link=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Davies |first=Norman |year=2008 |title=Europe at War 1939\u20131945: No Simple Victory |url= |location= |publisher= Pan Macmillan |page= 54|isbn=9780330472296 |author-link=Norman Davies}}</ref>\n\n== Soviet Union, Eastern Bloc and the Russian Federation ==\n{{see also|Media portrayal of the Ukrainian crisis}}<!-- NOTE: Hatnote templates should only be placed at the TOP of article subsections. -->\nThe [[Bolshevik]] movement and later the [[Soviet Union]] made frequent use of the \"fascist\" epithet coming from its conflict with the early German and Italian fascist movements. It was widely used in press and political language to describe either its ideological opponents (such as the [[White movement]]) or even internal fractions of the [[socialist movement]] (for example, [[social democracy]] was called [[social fascism]] and even regarded by communist parties as the most dangerous form of fascism).<ref name=\"Draper\">{{cite journal |last1=Draper |first1=Theodore|author-link=Theodore Draper|date=February 1969 |title=The Ghost of Social-Fascism |url=https://www.commentarymagazine.com/articles/the-ghost-of-social-fascism/ |journal=[[Commentary\u00a0(magazine)|Commentary]] |volume= |issue= |pages= 29\u201342 |doi= |access-date= }}</ref> In Germany, the [[Communist Party of Germany]] which had been largely controlled by the Soviet leadership since 1928 used the epithet \"fascism\" to describe both the social democrats and the [[Nazi movement]]; in Soviet usage the German Nazis were described as \"fascists\" until 1939, when the [[Molotov\u2013Ribbentrop Pact]] was signed, after which [[Nazi\u2013Soviet economic relations (1934\u201341)|Nazi\u2013Soviet relations]] started to be presented positively in Soviet propaganda.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}} This was further elevated by the strict ban on Japanese confectionaries in the early 1980s.\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-1986-0813-460, Berlin, Parade von Kampfgruppen zum Mauerbau.jpg|thumb|left|[[East Germany|East German]] military parade in 1986, celebrating the \"25th anniversary of the Anti-Fascist Protection Wall\", i.e. the [[Berlin Wall]]]]\nAfter the [[Operation Barbarossa|Nazi invasion of the Soviet Union]] in 1941, \"fascist\" was used in the Soviet Union to describe virtually any anti-Soviet activity or opinion. According to [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]], fascism was the \"final phase of crisis of [[bourgeoisie]]\", which \"in fascism sought refuge\" from \"inherent contradictions of [[capitalism]]\". As a result of this approach, it was almost every Western capitalist country that was \"fascist\", with the [[Third Reich]] being just the \"most [[reactionary]]\" one.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://militera.lib.ru/h/istoriya_voyny_na_tihom_okeane/16.html | title=\u041d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0444\u0430\u0448\u0438\u0437\u043c\u0430 \u0438 \u0437\u0430\u0434\u0430\u0447\u0438 \u041a\u043e\u043c\u043c\u0443\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0432 \u0431\u043e\u0440\u044c\u0431\u0435 \u0437\u0430 \u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0433\u043e \u043a\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0438\u0432 \u0444\u0430\u0448\u0438\u0437\u043c\u0430 | work=7th Comintern Congress | date=20 August 1935 | accessdate=2015-08-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://militera.lib.ru/h/12/01/02.html | title=\u0424\u0430\u0448\u0438\u0437\u043c \u2013 \u043d\u0430\u0438\u0431\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0435 \u043c\u0440\u0430\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0438\u043c\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0437\u043c\u0430 | work=\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0432\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0439 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0439\u043d\u044b 1939\u20131945 \u0433\u0433. | date=1973 | accessdate=2015-08-31}}</ref>  For example, the international investigation on [[Katyn massacre]] was described as \"fascist libel\"<ref>[[Robert Stiller]], \"Semantyka zbrodni\"</ref> and the [[Warsaw Uprising]] as \"illegal and organised by fascists\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.e-warszawa.com/e-warszawa/1944-powstanie | title=1944 \u2013 Powstanie Warszawskie | publisher=e-Warszawa.com | accessdate=2015-08-31}}</ref> Communist [[S\u0142u\u017cba Bezpiecze\u0144stwa]] described [[Trotskyism]], [[Titoism]] and [[imperialism]] as \"variants of fascism\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://katalog.bip.ipn.gov.pl/showDetails.do?idx=P&katalogId=2&subpageKatalogId=2&pageNo=1&nameId=18103&osobaId=33354& | title=Dane osoby z katalogu funkcjonariuszy aparatu bezpiecze\u0144stwa \u2013 Franciszek Prze\u017adzia\u0142 | publisher=Instytut Pami\u0119ci Narodowej | date=1951 | access-date=2015-08-31 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120080346/http://katalog.bip.ipn.gov.pl/showDetails.do?idx=P&katalogId=2&subpageKatalogId=2&pageNo=1&nameId=18103&osobaId=33354& | archive-date=November 20, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThis use continued into the [[Cold War]] era and the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]].  The Soviet-backed [[German Democratic Republic]]'s official name for the [[Berlin Wall]] was the \"[[Post-World War II anti-fascism|Anti-Fascist]] Protection Rampart\" ({{lang-de|Antifaschistischer Schutzwall}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goethe.de/ges/ztg/thm/ddg/en1748571.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409133940/http://www.goethe.de/ges/ztg/thm/ddg/en1748571.htm |archive-date=9 April 2008 |title=Goethe-Institut \u2013 Topics \u2013 German-German History Goethe-Institut |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=9 April 2008 |access-date=6 August 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>  During [[the Barricades]] in January 1991, which followed the May 1990 [[On the Restoration of Independence of the Republic of Latvia|declared restoration of independence]] of [[Republic of Latvia]] from the [[Soviet Union]], the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Communist Party]] declared that \"fascism was reborn in Latvia.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://coldwarsites.net/country/latvia/the-museum-of-the-barricades-of-1991-riga/ |title=The Museum of the Barricades of 1991, Riga}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2014, during the [[Euromaidan]] demonstrations, the \"Slavic Anti-fascist Front\" was created in Crimea by Russian MP [[Aleksey Zhuravlyov (politician)|Aleksey Zhuravlyov]] and Crimean [[Russian Unity]] party leader (and future [[Head of the Republic of Crimea]]) [[Sergey Aksyonov]] to oppose \"fascist uprising\" in Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/the-battle-for-kiev-begins | title=The Battle for Kiev Begins | publisher=Daily Beast| date=2014-02-18 | accessdate=2019-03-24| author=Oleg Shynkarenko}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|author=Elizabeth A. Wood|year=2015|title=Roots of Russia's War in Ukraine|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Woodrow Wilson Center Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0231801386}}</ref>  After the February [[2014 Ukrainian revolution]], through the [[annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation]] and the outbreak of the [[war in Donbass]], [[Russian nationalism|Russian nationalists]] and media used the term.  They frequently described the Ukrainian government after [[Euromaidan]] as \"fascist\" or \"Nazi\",<ref>{{cite web | url=http://time.com/3545855/russia-ukraine-war-history/ | title=Russians Re-write History to Slur Ukraine Over War | publisher=Time | date=2014-10-29 | accessdate=2014-10-30 | author=Simon Shuster}}</ref><ref name=NYB140320>{{cite web | url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2014/mar/20/fascism-russia-and-ukraine/ | title=Fascism, Russia, and Ukraine | work=The New York Review of Books | date=20 March 2014 | accessdate=22 July 2014 | last=Snyder |first= Timothy}}</ref> at the same time accusing them of \"[[Antisemitic canard|Jewish influence]]\" or spreading \"[[gay propaganda]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://blogs.ft.com/the-world/2014/03/fascism-a-useful-insult/|title = Fascism: a useful insult|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = Financial Times|last = Wagstyl|first = Stefan}}</ref>\n\n== Western politics ==\n\nIn 1944, the acclaimed English writer [[George Orwell]] had this to say about the term's overuse as an [[epithet]]:\n\n{{quote|text=It will be seen that, as used, the word \u2018Fascism\u2019 is almost entirely meaningless. In conversation, of course, it is used even more wildly than in print. I have heard it applied to farmers, shopkeepers, Social Credit, corporal punishment, fox-hunting, bull-fighting, the 1922 Committee, the 1941 Committee, Kipling, Gandhi, Chiang Kai-Shek, homosexuality, Priestley\u2019s broadcasts, Youth Hostels, astrology, women, dogs and I do not know what else... the people who recklessly fling the word \u2018Fascist\u2019 in every direction attach at any rate an emotional significance to it. By \u2018Fascism\u2019 they mean, roughly speaking, something cruel, unscrupulous, arrogant, obscurantist, anti-liberal and anti-working-class. Except for the relatively small number of Fascist sympathizers, almost any English person would accept \u2018bully\u2019 as a synonym for \u2018Fascist\u2019. That is about as near to a definition as this much-abused word has come.<ref>Rosman, Artur Sebastian. \"[https://bookhaven.stanford.edu/2017/02/orwell-watch-27-what-is-fascism/]\", ''Orwell Watch'', 2017-02-19.</ref>}}\n\nIn the 1980s, the term was used by leftist critics to describe the [[Presidency of Ronald Reagan|Reagan administration]]. The term was later used in the 2000s to describe the administration of [[Presidency of George W. Bush|George W. Bush]] by its critics and in the late 2010s to describe the candidacy and administration of [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Donald Trump]]. In her 1970 book ''Beyond Mere Obedience'', radical activist and theologian [[Dorothee S\u00f6lle]] coined the term \"[[Christofascism|Christofascist]]\" to describe [[fundamentalist Christians]].<ref>{{Cite book|author=[[Dorothee S\u00f6lle]] |year=1970|title=Beyond Mere Obedience: Reflections on a Christian Ethic for the Future |publisher=Augsburg Publishing House|location=Minneapolis | url=https://books.google.com/?id=zbeCGwAACAAJ&dq}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Confessing Christ in a Post-Christendom Context. |url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-66279081 |quote= ... shall we say this, represent this, live this, without seeming to endorse the kind of christomonism (Dorothee Solle called it \"Christofascism\"! ...  |publisher=The Ecumenical Review |date=July 1, 2000 |accessdate=2007-12-23 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|first=Sarah K. |last=Pinnock |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=The Theology of Dorothee Soelle |url=https://books.google.com/?id=56_VviorwEsC&dq |quote= ... of establishing a dubious moral superiority to justify organized violence on a massive scale, a perversion of Christianity she called Christofascism. ...  |isbn=1-56338-404-3 |publisher=Trinity Press International |year=2003 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, [[Samantha Power]] (lecturer at the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]] at [[Harvard University]]) reflected Orwell's words from 60 years prior when she stated: \"Fascism \u2013 unlike communism, socialism, capitalism, or conservatism \u2013 is a smear word more often used to brand one's foes than it is a descriptor used to shed light on them\".<ref>Power, Samantha. \"[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE0DB153AF931A35756C0A9629C8B63 The Original Axis of Evil]\", ''[[The New York Times]]'', 2004-05-02.</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the [[European Court of Human Rights]] found contrary to the Article 10 (freedom of expression) of [[ECHR]] fining a journalist for calling a right-wing journalist \"local neo-fascist\", regarding the statement as a value-judgment acceptable in the circumstances.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cmiskp.echr.coe.int/tkp197/view.asp?action=html&documentId=811485&portal=hbkm&source=externalbydocnumber&table=F69A27FD8FB86142BF01C1166DEA398649 |title=Case of Karman v. Russia (Application no. 29372/02) Judgment |publisher=European Court of Human Rights |date=March 14, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn response to multiple authors<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/this-is-how-fascism-comes-to-america/2016/05/17/c4e32c58-1c47-11e6-8c7b-6931e66333e7_story.html|title=This is how fascism comes to America|last=Kagan|first=Rober|date=May 18, 2016|website=The Washington Post|publisher=The Washington Post Media|access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-35050186|title='Racist', 'fascist', 'utterly repellent': What the world said about Donald Trump|last=|first=|date=December 9, 2015|website=BBC News|publisher=BBC|access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/going-there-with-donald-trump|title=Going There with Donald Trump|last=Gopnik|first=Adam|date=May 11, 2016|website=The New Yorker|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast|access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://highlandernews.org/20877/donald-trumps-fascist-tendencies/|title=Donald Trump\u2019s fascist tendencies|last=Swift|first=Nathan|date=October 26, 2015|website=The Highlander|publisher=Highlander Newspaper|access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/donald-trump/12041188/Donald-Trump-is-an-outright-fascist-who-should-be-banned-from-Britain-today.html|title=Donald Trump is an outright fascist who should be banned from Britain today|last=Hodges|first=Dan|date=December 9, 2015|website=The Telegraph|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> claiming that the then-presidential candidate Donald Trump was a \"fascist\", a 2016 article for [[Vox Media|Vox]] cited five historians who study fascism\u2014including [[Roger Griffin]], author of ''The Nature of Fascism''\u2014who stated that Trump either does not hold and even is opposed to several political viewpoints that are integral to fascism, including viewing violence as an inherent good and an inherent rejection of or opposition to a democratic system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2015/12/10/9886152/donald-trump-fascism|title=I asked 5 fascism experts whether Donald Trump is a fascist. Here's what they said.|last=Matthews|first=Dylan|date=May 19, 2016|website=Vox|publisher=Vox Media|access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Possible explanations for casual uses ==\n{{quote|text=They employ massive overkill strategy, there are 30, 20 to 30 marshals daily inside the courtroom, it has the atmosphere of an arms camp, the law against us is rigged [...] and our claims that this law violates our constitutional rights and it\u2019s the same way that we claim that Mayor Daley didn't have the right to deny us a permit to march or to assemble in the park [...]. I think it points a direction in the future which is that the government embarked on a course of fascism.|sign=[[Abbie Hoffman]]|source=[[Viking Youth Power Hour]] interview, November 1969<ref>\"[http://law2.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/chicago7/hoffmaninterview.html An Interview About the Trial with Abbie Hoffman]\"</ref>}}\nSeveral [[Marxist philosophy|Marxist theories]] back up particular uses of fascism beyond its usual remit. For instance, [[Nicos Poulantzas]]'s theory of [[state monopoly capitalism]] could be associated with the idea of a [[military-industrial complex]] to suggest that 1960s America had a fascist social structure, though this kind of [[Maoism|Maoist]] or [[Guevarism|Guevarist]] analysis often underpinned the rhetorical depiction of [[Cold War]] authoritarians as fascists.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nSome Marxist groups, such as the Indian section of the [[Fourth International (post-reunification)|Fourth International]] and the [[Mansoor Hekmat#Views|Hekmatist]] groups in Iran and Iraq, have provided analytical accounts as to why the term \"fascist\" should be applied to groups such as the [[Hindutva]] movement, the [[Iranian Revolution|1979 Islamic Iranian regime]] or the [[Islamism|Islamist]] sections of the [[Iraqi insurgency (2003\u20132011)|Iraqi insurgency]]. Other scholars contend that the traditional meaning of the term \"fascism\" does not apply to Hindutva groups and may hinder an analysis of their activities.<ref name=\"Refute\">{{cite news |url=http://world.christianpost.com/article/20031219/1016.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061113192335/http://world.christianpost.com/article/20031219/1016.htm |archivedate=November 13, 2006 |title=RSS neither Nationalist nor Fascist, Indian Christian priest's research concludes |publisher=[[The Christian Post]] |first=Surojit |last=Chatterjee |date=December 19, 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.expressindia.com/ie/daily/19980823/23550294.html |title=RSS neither nationalist nor fascist, says Christian priest after research |publisher=[[The Indian Express]] |author=P. Venugopal |date=August 23, 1998 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040722005929/http://www.expressindia.com/ie/daily/19980823/23550294.html |archive-date=July 22, 2004 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | author = Walter K. Andersen, Shridhar D. Damle |date=May 1989 | title = The Brotherhood in Saffron: The Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh and Hindu Revivalism | journal = [[American Academy of Political and Social Science#The Annals|Annals of the American Academy of Political and Social Science]] | volume = 503 | pages = 156\u201357 | doi = 10.1177/0002716289503001021 }}</ref><ref>''Ethnic and Racial Studies'', Volume 23, Number 3, May 2000, pp. 407\u2013441 [[International Standard Serial Number|ISSN]] 0141-9870 print/ISSN 1466-4356 online.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[Chaplinsky v. New Hampshire]]''\n* [[Definitions of fascism]]\n* [[Godwin's law]]\n* ''[[Reductio ad Hitlerum]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote|Fascism}}\n* [[Iivi Masso]] (19 February 2009). [https://web.archive.org/web/20110727082231/http://epl.ekspress.ee/artikkel/459417 \"Fa\u0161ism kui propaganda t\u00f6\u00f6riist\"] (''Fascism as a tool of propaganda''). Printed in [[Eesti P\u00e4evaleht]].\n\n{{Fascism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fascist (Epithet)}}\n[[Category:Article 10 of the European Convention on Human Rights]]\n[[Category:Pejorative terms for people]]\n[[Category:Political terminology]]\n[[Category:Fascism]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{more citations needed|date=October 2009}}\n{{Fascism sidebar|expanded=Related}}\n'''Fascist''' has been used as a [[pejorative]] [[epithet]] against a wide range of individuals, political movements, governments, public and private institutions since the emergence of [[fascism]] in [[Europe]] in the 1920s.\n\nThe widespread use of this term as an insult was noted as early as 1944, when British writer [[George Orwell]] commented that, in the [[United Kingdom]], \"the word 'Fascism' is almost entirely meaningless\" and that \"almost any English person would accept \u2018bully\u2019 as a synonym for \u2018Fascist\u2019.\"<ref>[[George Orwell]], [http://orwell.ru/library/articles/As_I_Please/english/efasc What is Fascism?], 1944</ref>\n\nIn the [[Soviet Union]], the epithets \"fascist\" and \"fascism\" were used to describe [[Anti-Sovietism|anti-Soviet]] activism and beliefs, such as [[enemy of the people|enemies of the people]]. This usage also spread to other [[Eastern bloc]] countries under Soviet [[Warsaw pact]] domination, such as [[East Germany]], where the [[Berlin Wall]] was known as the \"Anti-Fascist Protection Wall\". The term \"anti-fascist\" became ubiquitous in the Eastern bloc, where it became synonymous with the [[communist party]] line and denoted the struggle against [[dissenter]]s and against the broader [[Western world]].<ref name=\"Agethen\">{{cite book |last1= Agethen |first1= Manfred |last2= Jesse |first2= Eckhard |author-link2= Eckhard Jesse |last3= Neubert |first3= Ehrhart |year= 2002 |title= Der missbrauchte Antifaschismus |url= |location= Freiburg |publisher= Verlag Herder |page= |isbn= 978-3451280177 |author-link=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Davies |first=Norman |year=2008 |title=Europe at War 1939\u20131945: No Simple Victory |url= |location= |publisher= Pan Macmillan |page= 54|isbn=9780330472296 |author-link=Norman Davies}}</ref>\n\n== Soviet Union, Eastern bloc and the Russian Federation ==\n{{see also|Media portrayal of the Ukrainian crisis}}<!-- NOTE: Hatnote templates should only be placed at the TOP of article subsections. -->\nThe [[Bolshevik]] movement and later the [[Soviet Union]] made frequent use of the \"fascist\" epithet coming from its conflict with the early German and Italian fascist movements. It was widely used in press and political language to describe either its ideological opponents (such as the [[White movement]]) or even internal fractions of the [[socialist movement]] (for example, [[social democracy]] was called [[social fascism]] and even regarded by communist parties as the most dangerous form of fascism<ref name=\"Draper\">{{cite journal |last1=Draper |first1=Theodore|author-link=Theodore Draper|date=February 1969 |title=The Ghost of Social-Fascism |url=https://www.commentarymagazine.com/articles/the-ghost-of-social-fascism/ |journal=[[Commentary\u00a0(magazine)|Commentary]] |volume= |issue= |pages= 29\u201342 |doi= |access-date= }}</ref>). In Germany the [[Communist Party of Germany]], that had been largely controlled by the Soviet leadership since 1928, used the epithet \"fascism\" to describe both the social democrats and the [[Nazi movement]]; in Soviet usage the German Nazis were described as \"fascists\" until 1939, when the [[Molotov\u2013Ribbentrop Pact]] was signed, after which [[Nazi\u2013Soviet economic relations (1934\u201341)|Nazi\u2013Soviet relations]] started to be presented positively in Soviet propaganda.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}} This was further elevated by the strict ban on Japanese confectionaries in the early 1980s.\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-1986-0813-460, Berlin, Parade von Kampfgruppen zum Mauerbau.jpg|thumb|left|[[East Germany|East German]] military parade in 1986, celebrating the \"25th anniversary of the Anti-Fascist Protection Wall\", i.e. the [[Berlin Wall]]]]\nAfter the [[Operation Barbarossa|Nazi invasion of the Soviet Union]] in 1941, \"fascist\" was used in the Soviet Union to describe virtually any anti-Soviet activity or opinion. According to [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]], fascism was the \"final phase of crisis of [[bourgeoisie]]\", which \"in fascism sought refuge\" from \"inherent contradictions of [[capitalism]]\". As a result of this approach, it was almost every Western capitalist country that was \"fascist\", with the [[Third Reich]] being just the \"most [[reactionary]]\" one.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://militera.lib.ru/h/istoriya_voyny_na_tihom_okeane/16.html | title=\u041d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0444\u0430\u0448\u0438\u0437\u043c\u0430 \u0438 \u0437\u0430\u0434\u0430\u0447\u0438 \u041a\u043e\u043c\u043c\u0443\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0432 \u0431\u043e\u0440\u044c\u0431\u0435 \u0437\u0430 \u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0447\u0435\u0433\u043e \u043a\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0438\u0432 \u0444\u0430\u0448\u0438\u0437\u043c\u0430 | work=7th Comintern Congress | date=20 August 1935 | accessdate=2015-08-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://militera.lib.ru/h/12/01/02.html | title=\u0424\u0430\u0448\u0438\u0437\u043c \u2013 \u043d\u0430\u0438\u0431\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0435 \u043c\u0440\u0430\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0438\u043c\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0437\u043c\u0430 | work=\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0432\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0439 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0439\u043d\u044b 1939\u20131945 \u0433\u0433. | date=1973 | accessdate=2015-08-31}}</ref>  For example, the international investigation on [[Katyn massacre]] was described as \"fascist libel\"<ref>[[Robert Stiller]], \"Semantyka zbrodni\"</ref> and the [[Warsaw Uprising]] as \"illegal and organised by fascists\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.e-warszawa.com/e-warszawa/1944-powstanie | title=1944 \u2013 Powstanie Warszawskie | publisher=e-Warszawa.com | accessdate=2015-08-31}}</ref> Communist [[S\u0142u\u017cba Bezpiecze\u0144stwa]] described [[Trotskyism]], [[Titoism]] and [[imperialism]] as \"variants of fascism\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://katalog.bip.ipn.gov.pl/showDetails.do?idx=P&katalogId=2&subpageKatalogId=2&pageNo=1&nameId=18103&osobaId=33354& | title=Dane osoby z katalogu funkcjonariuszy aparatu bezpiecze\u0144stwa \u2013 Franciszek Prze\u017adzia\u0142 | publisher=Instytut Pami\u0119ci Narodowej | date=1951 | access-date=2015-08-31 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120080346/http://katalog.bip.ipn.gov.pl/showDetails.do?idx=P&katalogId=2&subpageKatalogId=2&pageNo=1&nameId=18103&osobaId=33354& | archive-date=November 20, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThis use continued into the [[Cold War]] era and the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]].  The Soviet-backed [[German Democratic Republic]]'s official name for the [[Berlin Wall]] was the \"[[Post-World War II anti-fascism|Anti-Fascist]] Protection Rampart\" ({{lang-de|Antifaschistischer Schutzwall}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goethe.de/ges/ztg/thm/ddg/en1748571.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409133940/http://www.goethe.de/ges/ztg/thm/ddg/en1748571.htm |archive-date=9 April 2008 |title=Goethe-Institut \u2013 Topics \u2013 German-German History Goethe-Institut |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=9 April 2008 |access-date=6 August 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>  During [[the Barricades]] in January 1991, which followed the May 1990 [[On the Restoration of Independence of the Republic of Latvia|declared restoration of independence]] of [[Republic of Latvia]] from the [[Soviet Union]], the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Communist Party]] declared that \"fascism was reborn in Latvia.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://coldwarsites.net/country/latvia/the-museum-of-the-barricades-of-1991-riga/ |title=The Museum of the Barricades of 1991, Riga}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2014, during the [[Euromaidan]] demonstrations, the \"Slavic Anti-fascist Front\" was created in Crimea by Russian MP [[Aleksey Zhuravlyov (politician)|Aleksey Zhuravlyov]] and Crimean [[Russian Unity]] party leader (and future [[Head of the Republic of Crimea]]) [[Sergey Aksyonov]] to oppose \"fascist uprising\" in Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/the-battle-for-kiev-begins | title=The Battle for Kiev Begins | publisher=Daily Beast| date=2014-02-18 | accessdate=2019-03-24| author=Oleg Shynkarenko}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|author=Elizabeth A. Wood|year=2015|title=Roots of Russia's War in Ukraine|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Woodrow Wilson Center Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0231801386}}</ref>  After the February [[2014 Ukrainian revolution]], through the [[annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation]] and the outbreak of the [[war in Donbass]], [[Russian nationalism|Russian nationalists]] and media used the term.  They frequently described the Ukrainian government after [[Euromaidan]] as \"fascist\" or \"Nazi\",<ref>{{cite web | url=http://time.com/3545855/russia-ukraine-war-history/ | title=Russians Re-write History to Slur Ukraine Over War | publisher=Time | date=2014-10-29 | accessdate=2014-10-30 | author=Simon Shuster}}</ref><ref name=NYB140320>{{cite web | url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2014/mar/20/fascism-russia-and-ukraine/ | title=Fascism, Russia, and Ukraine | work=The New York Review of Books | date=20 March 2014 | accessdate=22 July 2014 | last=Snyder |first= Timothy}}</ref> at the same time accusing them of \"[[Antisemitic canard|Jewish influence]]\" or spreading \"[[gay propaganda]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://blogs.ft.com/the-world/2014/03/fascism-a-useful-insult/|title = Fascism: a useful insult|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = Financial Times|last = Wagstyl|first = Stefan}}</ref>\n\n== Western politics ==\n\nIn 1944, the acclaimed English writer [[George Orwell]] had this to say about the term's overuse as an [[epithet]]:\n\n{{quote|text=It will be seen that, as used, the word \u2018Fascism\u2019 is almost entirely meaningless. In conversation, of course, it is used even more wildly than in print. I have heard it applied to farmers, shopkeepers, Social Credit, corporal punishment, fox-hunting, bull-fighting, the 1922 Committee, the 1941 Committee, Kipling, Gandhi, Chiang Kai-Shek, homosexuality, Priestley\u2019s broadcasts, Youth Hostels, astrology, women, dogs and I do not know what else... the people who recklessly fling the word \u2018Fascist\u2019 in every direction attach at any rate an emotional significance to it. By \u2018Fascism\u2019 they mean, roughly speaking, something cruel, unscrupulous, arrogant, obscurantist, anti-liberal and anti-working-class. Except for the relatively small number of Fascist sympathizers, almost any English person would accept \u2018bully\u2019 as a synonym for \u2018Fascist\u2019. That is about as near to a definition as this much-abused word has come.<ref>Rosman, Artur Sebastian. \"[https://bookhaven.stanford.edu/2017/02/orwell-watch-27-what-is-fascism/]\", ''Orwell Watch'', 2017-02-19.</ref>}}\n\nIn the 1980s, the term was used by leftist critics to describe the [[Presidency of Ronald Reagan|Reagan administration]]. The term was later used in the 2000s to describe the administration of [[Presidency of George W. Bush|George W. Bush]] by its critics and in the late 2010s to describe the candidacy and administration of [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Donald Trump]]. In her 1970 book ''Beyond Mere Obedience'', radical activist and theologian [[Dorothee S\u00f6lle]] coined the term \"[[Christofascism|Christofascist]]\" to describe [[fundamentalist Christians]].<ref>{{Cite book|author=[[Dorothee S\u00f6lle]] |year=1970|title=Beyond Mere Obedience: Reflections on a Christian Ethic for the Future |publisher=Augsburg Publishing House|location=Minneapolis | url=https://books.google.com/?id=zbeCGwAACAAJ&dq}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Confessing Christ in a Post-Christendom Context. |url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-66279081 |quote= ... shall we say this, represent this, live this, without seeming to endorse the kind of christomonism (Dorothee Solle called it \"Christofascism\"! ...  |publisher=The Ecumenical Review |date=July 1, 2000 |accessdate=2007-12-23 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|first=Sarah K. |last=Pinnock |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=The Theology of Dorothee Soelle |url=https://books.google.com/?id=56_VviorwEsC&dq |quote= ... of establishing a dubious moral superiority to justify organized violence on a massive scale, a perversion of Christianity she called Christofascism. ...  |isbn=1-56338-404-3 |publisher=Trinity Press International |year=2003 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, [[Samantha Power]] (lecturer at the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]] at [[Harvard University]]) reflected Orwell's words from 60 years prior when she stated: \"Fascism \u2013 unlike communism, socialism, capitalism, or conservatism \u2013 is a smear word more often used to brand one's foes than it is a descriptor used to shed light on them\".<ref>Power, Samantha. \"[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE0DB153AF931A35756C0A9629C8B63 The Original Axis of Evil]\", ''[[The New York Times]]'', 2004-05-02.</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the [[European Court of Human Rights]] found contrary to the Article 10 (freedom of expression) of [[ECHR]] fining a journalist for calling a right-wing journalist \"local neo-fascist\", regarding the statement as a value-judgment acceptable in the circumstances.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cmiskp.echr.coe.int/tkp197/view.asp?action=html&documentId=811485&portal=hbkm&source=externalbydocnumber&table=F69A27FD8FB86142BF01C1166DEA398649 |title=Case of Karman v. Russia (Application no. 29372/02) Judgment |publisher=European Court of Human Rights |date=March 14, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn response to multiple authors<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/this-is-how-fascism-comes-to-america/2016/05/17/c4e32c58-1c47-11e6-8c7b-6931e66333e7_story.html|title=This is how fascism comes to America|last=Kagan|first=Rober|date=May 18, 2016|website=The Washington Post|publisher=The Washington Post Media|access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-35050186|title='Racist', 'fascist', 'utterly repellent': What the world said about Donald Trump|last=|first=|date=December 9, 2015|website=BBC News|publisher=BBC|access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/going-there-with-donald-trump|title=Going There with Donald Trump|last=Gopnik|first=Adam|date=May 11, 2016|website=The New Yorker|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast|access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://highlandernews.org/20877/donald-trumps-fascist-tendencies/|title=Donald Trump\u2019s fascist tendencies|last=Swift|first=Nathan|date=October 26, 2015|website=The Highlander|publisher=Highlander Newspaper|access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/donald-trump/12041188/Donald-Trump-is-an-outright-fascist-who-should-be-banned-from-Britain-today.html|title=Donald Trump is an outright fascist who should be banned from Britain today|last=Hodges|first=Dan|date=December 9, 2015|website=The Telegraph|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> claiming that the then-presidential candidate Donald Trump was a \"fascist\", a 2016 article for [[Vox Media|Vox]] cited five historians who study fascism\u2014including [[Roger Griffin]], author of ''The Nature of Fascism''\u2014who stated that Trump either does not hold and even is opposed to several political viewpoints that are integral to fascism, including viewing violence as an inherent good and an inherent rejection of or opposition to a democratic system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2015/12/10/9886152/donald-trump-fascism|title=I asked 5 fascism experts whether Donald Trump is a fascist. Here's what they said.|last=Matthews|first=Dylan|date=May 19, 2016|website=Vox|publisher=Vox Media|access-date=August 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Possible explanations for casual uses ==\n{{quote|text=They employ massive overkill strategy, there are 30, 20 to 30 marshals daily inside the courtroom, it has the atmosphere of an arms camp, the law against us is rigged [...] and our claims that this law violates our constitutional rights and it\u2019s the same way that we claim that Mayor Daley didn't have the right to deny us a permit to march or to assemble in the park [...]. I think it points a direction in the future which is that the government embarked on a course of fascism.|sign=[[Abbie Hoffman]]|source=[[Viking Youth Power Hour]] interview, November 1969<ref>\"[http://law2.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/chicago7/hoffmaninterview.html An Interview About the Trial with Abbie Hoffman]\"</ref>}}\nSeveral [[Marxist philosophy|Marxist theories]] back up particular uses of fascism beyond its usual remit. For instance, [[Nicos Poulantzas]]'s theory of [[state monopoly capitalism]] could be associated with the idea of a [[military-industrial complex]] to suggest that 1960s America had a fascist social structure, though this kind of [[Maoism|Maoist]] or [[Guevarism|Guevarist]] analysis often underpinned the rhetorical depiction of [[Cold War]] authoritarians as fascists.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nSome Marxist groups, such as the Indian section of the [[Fourth International (post-reunification)|Fourth International]] and the [[Mansoor Hekmat#Views|Hekmatist]] groups in Iran and Iraq, have provided analytical accounts as to why the term \"fascist\" should be applied to groups such as the [[Hindutva]] movement, the [[Iranian Revolution|1979 Islamic Iranian regime]] or the [[Islamism|Islamist]] sections of the [[Iraqi insurgency (2003\u20132011)|Iraqi insurgency]]. Other scholars contend that the traditional meaning of the term \"fascism\" does not apply to Hindutva groups and may hinder an analysis of their activities.<ref name=\"Refute\">{{cite news |url=http://world.christianpost.com/article/20031219/1016.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061113192335/http://world.christianpost.com/article/20031219/1016.htm |archivedate=November 13, 2006 |title=RSS neither Nationalist nor Fascist, Indian Christian priest's research concludes |publisher=[[The Christian Post]] |first=Surojit |last=Chatterjee |date=December 19, 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.expressindia.com/ie/daily/19980823/23550294.html |title=RSS neither nationalist nor fascist, says Christian priest after research |publisher=[[The Indian Express]] |author=P. Venugopal |date=August 23, 1998 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040722005929/http://www.expressindia.com/ie/daily/19980823/23550294.html |archive-date=July 22, 2004 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | author = Walter K. Andersen, Shridhar D. Damle |date=May 1989 | title = The Brotherhood in Saffron: The Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh and Hindu Revivalism | journal = [[American Academy of Political and Social Science#The Annals|Annals of the American Academy of Political and Social Science]] | volume = 503 | pages = 156\u201357 | doi = 10.1177/0002716289503001021 }}</ref><ref>''Ethnic and Racial Studies'', Volume 23, Number 3, May 2000, pp. 407\u2013441 [[International Standard Serial Number|ISSN]] 0141-9870 print/ISSN 1466-4356 online.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[Chaplinsky v. New Hampshire]]''\n* [[Definitions of fascism]]\n* [[Godwin's law]]\n* ''[[Reductio ad Hitlerum]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote|Fascism}}\n* [[Iivi Masso]] (19 February 2009). [https://web.archive.org/web/20110727082231/http://epl.ekspress.ee/artikkel/459417 \"Fa\u0161ism kui propaganda t\u00f6\u00f6riist\"] (''Fascism as a tool of propaganda''). Printed in [[Eesti P\u00e4evaleht]].\n\n{{Fascism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fascist (Epithet)}}\n[[Category:Article 10 of the European Convention on Human Rights]]\n[[Category:Pejorative terms for people]]\n[[Category:Political terminology]]\n[[Category:Fascism]]\n", "name_user": "Davide King", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSoviet Union, Eastern bloc and the Russian Federation:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fascist_(insult)"}
{"title_page": "Alpine newt", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| fossil_range = {{Geological range|Miocene|Recent|ref={{r|RecueroBuckley2014}}}}\n| genus = Ichthyosaura\n| species = alpestris\n| name = Alpine newt\n| image = Uhandre goimenditarra.jpg\n| image_caption = Two males during mating season\n| status = LC \n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = {{r|iucn}}\n| parent_authority = [[Pierre Andre Latreille|Latreille]], 1801\n| authority = ([[Josephus Nicolaus Laurenti|Laurenti]], 1768)\n| synonyms =\nAround 80,{{r|Frost2020}} including:\n* ''Triton alpestris'' {{small|(Laurenti, 1768)}}\n* ''Triturus alpestris'' {{small|(Dunn, 1918)}}\n* ''Mesotriton alpestris'' {{small|(Garc\u00eda-Par\u00eds, Montori, and Herrero, 2004)}}\n| range_map = Triturus alpestris dis.png\n}}\n\nThe '''alpine newt''' (''Ichthyosaura alpestris'') is a [[newt]] of the [[salamander]] order Caudata (or Urodela) in the class of [[amphibians]].\nIt was formerly known as ''[[Triturus]] alpestris'' and ''Mesotriton alpestris''.\n\n==Description==\n\n[[File:Bergmolchwerbung_2.jpg|thumb|left|Male (bright blue, left) courting a female (mottled brown, right) in a shallow pond]]\n\nThe alpine newt is a medium-sized, stocky newt species, with males reaching {{convert|8-10|cm|in|abbr=on}} and females {{convert|10-12|cm|in|abbr=on}}. The tail is half as long or slightly shorter than the rest of the body and laterally compressed. During life in water, both sexes develop a tail [[fin]], and males a low, smooth-edged crest on the back. The [[cloaca]] of males swells during breeding season. The skin is smooth during and granular outside breeding season, and velvety during the land phase.{{r|Sparreboom2014|p=213}}\n\nAlpine newts are blackish\u2013grey to bluish on the sides and the back, while their belly is an unspotted orange. Males also have a white band with black spots and a light blue flash running along the flanks, from the cheeks to the tail. Their crest, during breeding season, is white with regular dark spots. Females are of a more drab, mottled colour than males. Body shape and colour differ slightly among the subspecies.{{r|Sparreboom2014|p=213}}\n\n[[Larvae]] are 7\u20138 mm long after hatching and grow to {{convert|4-5|cm|in|abbr=on}}. They are usually light brown-yellow and darker towards the tail, which ends in a small, pointed filament.{{r|Sparreboom2014|p=215}}\n\n==Taxonomy and Systematics==\n\n===Nomenclature===\n\nThe alpine newt was first described in 1768, as ''Triton alpestris'' from mount [[\u00d6tscher]] in the Austrian Alps (''alpestris'' meaning \"alpine\" in Latin), by Austrian zoologist [[Josephus Nicolaus Laurenti]].{{r|Laurenti1768}} Laurenti thought that males, females and larvae were different species.{{r|Schmidtler2007}} Later, the alpine newt was placed in ''[[Triturus]]'' along with most other European newts. As this genus was found to contain several unrelated lineages, the alpine newt was split off as [[monotypic]] genus ''Mesotriton'' in 2004,{{r|Garcia-Paris2004}} which had been erected as a [[subgenus]] by [[Istv\u00e1n J\u00f3zsef Bolkay]] in 1928.{{r|Bolkay1928}} However, it was argued that a gilled newt Laurenti had described as ''Proteus tritonius'' in fact represented a larva of the alpine newt. The name ''Ichthyosaura'', introduced by [[Sonnini de Manoncourt]] and [[Latreille]] in 1801 for that larva,{{r|SonniniLatreille1802|p=310}} therefore has priority over ''Mesotriton'' and is the [[valid name (zoology)|valid]] genus name.{{r|1=Schmidtler2009|2=ThiesmeierSchulte2010|p2=9-10}}\n\n===Subspecies===\n\nThe subdivision of the alpine newt is controversial. A number of subspecies have been described, but many were not recognised by later authors. Differences in shape and colour are not consistent.{{r|1=Sparreboom2014|p1=214|2=ThiesmeierSchulte2010|p2=16-36}} However, there are clearly distinct ancient [[lineage (evolution)|lineages]] within the species (see section ''Evolution'' below). Several authors therefore argued that the alpine newt might even represent several [[cryptic species]].{{r|Frost2020|Raffaelli2018}} An article from 2018 accepted four species,{{r|Raffaelli2018}} but this has been considered premature in ''Amphibian Species of the World''.{{r|Frost2020}}\n\nFour subspecies were recognised in the ''Handbook of the Amphibians and Reptiles of Europe'' (2003),{{r|Rocek2003}} and this has been followed by a 2010 monograph{{r|ThiesmeierSchulte2010|p=16-36}} and ''Salamanders of the Old World'' (2014):{{r|Sparreboom2014|p=214}}\n\n*Alpine newt \u2013 ''I. a. alpestris'' {{small|(Laurenti, 1768)}}: The [[nominate subspecies|nominate]], northernmost and most widespread subspecies. It is not a [[natural group]]: Populations from western and central Europe form a lineage with ''I. a. cyreni'', while eastern populations are closer to the Greek alpine newt.{{r|RecueroBuckley2014}} These eastern populations have also been separated as species ''I. reiseri'' with three subspecies.{{r|Raffaelli2018}}\n\n*Apennine alpine newt \u2013 ''I. a. apuana'' {{small|(Gray, 1850)}}: Has also been recognised as species ''I. apuana'' and isolated populations from southern Italy as subspecies ''I. a. inexpectata''.{{r|Raffaelli2018}}\n\n*Cantabrian alpine newt \u2013 ''I. a. cyreni'' {{small|(Mertens & Muller, 1940)}}: Close to the western populations of ''I. a. alpestris''.{{r|RecueroBuckley2014}}\n\n*Greek alpine newt \u2013 ''I. a. veluchiensis'' {{small|(Wolterstorff, 1935)}}: Close to the eastern populations of ''I. a. alpestris''.{{r|RecueroBuckley2014}}\n\n==Distribution==\n\nThe alpine newt is native to continental Europe, with its subspecies occurring in different areas:{{r|1=Sparreboom2014|p1=214\u2013215|2=iucn|3=ThiesmeierSchulte2010|p3=39-46|4=RecueroBuckley2014|5=Raffaelli2018}}\n\n* The ''western group'' of the nominate subspecies ''I. a. alpestris'' occurs almost continuously from northwestern France over most of Germany and southern Poland to the northern [[Carpathians]] in Romania. It reaches southern Denmark in the north. In the south, it occurs until just north of Mediterranean France and in the Alps.\n\n* The ''eastern group'' of the nominate subspecies is found in the [[Balkan peninsula]] north of Greece, and until Bulgaria in the east as well as in the southern Carpathians in Romania.\n\n* The Appenine alpine newt (''I. a. apuana'') is separated from the northern subspecies by the [[Po valley]]. It occurs from extreme southeastern France over the [[Apennines]] until [[Lazio]] in central Italy. Isolated populations from three mountain lakes in [[Cantabria]] have also been considered as different subspecies, ''I. a. inexpectata''.\n\n* The Cantabrian alpine newt (''I. a. cyreni'') is found in the [[Cantabrian mountains]] of northern Spain, isolated from the rest of the species' range. An isolated population in the [[Sierra de Guadarrama]] of central Spain is probably the result of an introduction.\n\n* The Greek Alpine newt (''I. a. veluchiensis'') is found from the Greek mainland to the northern [[Peloponnese]], where the southernmost populations of the alpine newt occur.\n\nAlpine newts have been deliberately introduced to various places in Europe, including within the boundaries of cities such as [[Bremen]] and [[Berlin]].{{r|ThiesmeierSchulte2010|p3=39-46}} More distant introductions have occurred to [[Great Britain]], mainly England but also Scotland,{{r|BondNHSN}} and New Zealand.{{r|Bell2016}}\n\n==Habitat==\n\nLike other newts, the alpine newt depends on both humid, cover-rich land habitats as well as aquatic breeding sites. It tolerates a wide range of conditions. In its terrestrial phase, it is mainly found in forested and recently cleared areas, where it hides under logs, stones or in small [[burrow]]s. Breeding sites can vary from temporary puddles to ponds, large reservoirs and quiet parts of streams, and the species is relatively tolerant regarding temperature and [[eutrophication]].{{r|Sparreboom2014|p=216}}\n\n==Life and behaviour==\n\n[[File:Love-Is-Blind-Indiscriminate-Female-Mating-Responses-to-Male-Courtship-Pheromones-in-Newts-pone.0056538.s001.ogv | thumb | right | Stages of [[courtship display]], filmed in captivity{{r|Wicker-ThomasTreer2013}}]]\n[[File:Mesotriton alpestris apuanus04.jpg | thumb | right | Paedomorphic adult (above) and larva (below) of subspecies ''I. a. apuana'']]\n[[File:Alpine_Newt_(Ichthyosaura_alpestris)_hibernating_in_dead_wood_(13537518605).jpg | thumb | right | Juvenile hibernating in dead wood]]\n\nThe aquatic phase starts as soon as ice starts to disappear, from February in the lowlands to June at higher altitudes, while egg-laying follows a few months later and can continue until August. Alpine newts tend to visit the same breeding sites again each year.{{r|Sparreboom2014|p=216}}\n\nBreeding behaviour occurs mainly in the morning and at dawn. Like in other newts, males perform a [[courtship display]], which differs somewhat from other species. The male first places himself in front of the female, remains static for a while and, fans its tail to stimulate the female and waves [[pheromones]] towards her. After leaning in and touching her snout, he creeps away, followed by the female. When she touches the base of his tail with her snout, he releases a sperm packet ([[spermatophore]]) and blocks the female's path so she picks it up with her cloaca. Several rounds of spermatophore deposition may follow. Males frequently interfere with rivals' display.{{r|Sparreboom2014|p=215}}  Experiments suggested that it is mainly male pheromones that trigger mating behaviour in females while colour and other visual cues are less relevant.{{r|Wicker-ThomasTreer2013}}\n\nFemales attach their eggs individually to water plants or other objects. They lay clutches of 70\u2013390 eggs, which are light grey-brown and 1.5\u20131.7 mm in diameter (with a 2.5\u20133 mm capsule). Incubation time depends on temperature, but larvae typically hatch after two to four weeks. They [[metamorphose]] into terrestrial [[eft]]s after around three months, again depending on temperature, but some larvae overwinter and metamorphose only in the next year. [[Paedomorphy]] (or neoteny), where adults retain a larva-like appearance with [[gill]]s and stay aquatic, is common. Paedomorphic and metamorphic newts can co-occur and interbreed, but appear to prefer different prey.{{r|Sparreboom2014|p=215}}\n\nThe alpine newt reaches [[sexual maturity]] at around three years in males, and four to five years in females, and can reach an age of ten years in lowland. At higher altitude, maturity is reached only after 9-11 years, and the newts can grow up to 30 years old.{{r|Sparreboom2014|p=215}}\n\nFeeding takes place mainly during the night. Alpine newts take various [[invertebrates]] such as [[earthworms]], [[isopod]]s, small insects and [[crane fly]] and [[mayfly]] larvae, but also eggs and larvae of other amphibians. Their predators include snakes, birds and fish.{{r|Sparreboom2014|p=216}}\n\n==Evolution==\n\nAlpine newt [[population]]s have separated since the [[Early Miocene]], around 20 [[million years ago]], according to a [[molecular phylogenetic]] estimate.{{r|RecueroBuckley2014}} Fossil remains of the alpine newt were found in the [[Pleistocene]] of Northern Italy.{{r|VillaBlain2018}} An older, [[Miocene]] fossil from Germany, ''[[Ichthyosaura randeckensis]]'', may be its [[sister species]].{{r|Schoch2013}}\n\nAnalyses showed that populations fall into a western and an eastern group. Each of these again contains two major [[Lineage (evolution)|lineages]], which only in part correspond to described [[subspecies]] (see below).{{r|RecueroBuckley2014|SotiropoulosEleftherakos2007}} These genetic differences suggest that the alpine newt may be a [[species complex|complex]] of several distinct species.{{r|RecueroBuckley2014|Frost2020|Raffaelli2018}} Higher temperatures during the [[Miocene]] or sea level oscillations may have separated early populations, leading to [[allopatric speciation]]. However, [[nuclear DNA|nuclear]] and [[mitochondrial DNA|mitochondrial DNA]] show different population structures, which may results from [[genetic admixture|admixture]] and [[introgression]] between lineages. The [[Quaternary glaciation]] probably led to cycles of population retreat, expansion and range shifts.{{r|RecueroBuckley2014}}\n\n==Threats and conservation==\n\nBecause of its overall large range and populations that are not severely fragmented, the alpine newt is classified as [[Least Concern]] by the [[International Union for the Conservation of Nature]]; the population trend however is \"Decreasing\".{{r|iucn}} Threats are similar to those affecting other newts and include mainly [[habitat destruction|destruction]] and [[water pollution|pollution]] of aquatic habitats, as well as the introduction of fish, especially [[salmonids]], to breeding sites.{{r|Sparreboom2014|p=216}} In the [[Montenegro|Montenegrin]] [[karst]] region, populations have declined as ponds created for cattle and human use were abandoned over the last decades.{{r|Sparreboom2014|p=216}}\n\nIntroduced alpine newts may themselves pose a threat to native amphibians if they carry disease. At least one introduced population in the United Kingdom was affected by [[chytridiomycosis]],{{r|iucn}} and for the exotic subspecies ''I. a. apuana'' in New Zealand, [[eradication]] was recommended.{{r|Bell2016}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist | 30em | refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Bell2016\">{{cite journal | last=Bell | first=B.D. | title = A review of potential alpine newt (''Ichthyosaura alpestris'') impacts on native frogs in New Zealand | journal = Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand | volume = 46 | issue=3\u20134 | year = 2016 | pages = 214\u2013231 | issn=0303-6758 | doi = 10.1080/03036758.2016.1216455}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Bolkay1928\">{{cite journal | last1 = Bolkay | first1 = J. | title = Die Sch\u00e4del der Salamandrinen, mit besonderer R\u00fccksicht auf ihre systematische Bedeutung | journal = Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Anatomie und Entwicklungsgeschichte | volume = 86 | issue = 3-4 | year = 1928 | pages = 259\u2013319 | issn = 0340-2061 |doi = 10.1007/BF02117989 | language = German}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BondNHSN\">{{cite url | last1 = Bond | first1 = I. | title = Alpine Newt | year = 2020 | publisher = Natural History Society of Northumbria | url = https://www.nhsn.ncl.ac.uk/interests/reptiles-amphibians/alpine-newt/ | accessdate = 5 April 2020 | archiveurl = | archive-date = 22 September 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190922004603/https://www.nhsn.ncl.ac.uk/interests/reptiles-amphibians/alpine-newt/ }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Frost2020\">{{ cite web |last=Frost |first=D.R. | year = 2020 | title = ''Ichthyosaura alpestris'' (Laurenti, 1768). Amphibian Species of the World: an Online Reference. Version 6.1 |url = https://amphibiansoftheworld.amnh.org/Amphibia/Caudata/Salamandridae/Pleurodelinae/Ichthyosaura/Ichthyosaura-alpestris  | accessdate = 21 March 2020 | publisher = American Museum of Natural History | location = New York, USA | doi = 10.5531/db.vz.0001}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Garcia-Paris2004\">{{ cite book | last1 = Garc\u00eda-Par\u00eds | first1=M. | last2 = Montori | first2 = A. |last3 = Herrero | first3 = P. |year = 2004 | title = Amphibia: Lissamphibia | series = Fauna Iberica | volume = 24 | publisher = Museo Nacional de Ciencias Naturales, Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Cient\u00edficas | location = Madrid | isbn = 8400082923 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"iucn\">{{ cite iucn | url = https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/59472/0 | title = ''Ichthyosaura alpestris'' (Alpine Newt) | accessdate = 28 March 2020 | display-authors = 3 |author1 = Jan Willem Arntzen | author2 = Mathieu Deno\u00ebl |author3 = Sergius Kuzmin | author4 = Vladimir Ishchenko | author5 = Pedro Beja | author6 = Franco Andreone | author7 = Robert Jehle | author8 = Per Nystr\u00f6m | author9 = Claude Miaud | author10 = Brandon Anthony